== Surgical technique == 
The rhomboid muscles, trapezius, levator scapulae and latissimus dorsi are transected. The neurovascular bundle consisting of the axillary artery, axillary vein and brachial plexus is ligated and cut. The area of the chest left exposed is then normally covered with a split-thickness [[skin graft]].<ref name="Malawer2001" />
== In the news ==
In 2008, Mr. David Nott, a British vascular surgeon in the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]] with [[Médecins Sans Frontières]] performed a forequarter amputation to save the life of a 16-year-old boy, whose arm had been severed by an injury. It is unclear whether the arm was bitten off by a [[hippopotamus]]<ref name=msf>[http://www.msf.org/msfinternational/invoke.cfm?objectid=FD0C8B07-15C5-F00A-255928173107DAB4&component=toolkit.article&method=full_html MSF: DRC: Amputation done after consultation via text messages] ''(Last accessed Fri 19 Dec 2008.)''</ref> or destroyed by crossfire in the conflict.<ref name=msf2>[http://www.msf.org.uk/msf_surgeons_experience_rutshuru_20081101.news MSF surgeon describes the situation in Rutshuru, Congo (DRC) - news - MSF UK] ''(Last accessed Fri 19 Dec 2008.)''</ref> He was left with a gangrenous stump and had a few days to live. It made the news because his colleague, Professor Meirion Thomas, sent pointers via [[SMS text message]].<ref name=bbc>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/7761994.stm BBC NEWS | Health | Surgeon saves boy's life by text] ''(Last accessed Fri 19 Dec 2008.)''</ref> The text message included 10 steps to be followed and finished by saying, "Easy! Good luck."<ref name=Medgadget>[http://www.medgadget.com/archives/2008/12/text_messaging_surgical_instructionsits_easy_good_luck.html Text Messaging Surgical Instructions...It's "Easy! Good Luck" - Medgadget] ''(Last accessed Fri 19 Dec 2008.)''</ref>

